#Mouloukhiya—a green leaf once banned as a food limited to kings 

Once upon a time there was an Egyptian king who got terribly sick one day. His healers recommended he drink this green soup made from the leaves of a plant we now call here in Egypt — Molokhia. The word Molokhia comes from the word ‘mulukia’ which means ‘of royalty’. Even though the plant started off its life as a royal remedy, it has now become a national staple that is part of every Egyptian’s diet almost from the moment one can start eating as a toddler. We all grow up on Molokhia, whether eating it with rice, bread, shrimp, rabbit, chicken or meat. Unlike many of its other green counterparts in the vegetable family like spinach or broccoli, molokhia is a favourite amongst kids, which is fantastic from a nutritional point of view as molokhia is a health gem containing high amounts of iron, magnesium, potassium, calcium alongside many other vitamins and minerals. Good for both the bones of the young ones and the guts of the old ones, molokhia has been a part of our diet for hundreds of years and is here to stay. 

It is used as a vegetable and is mainly eaten in Egypt, the Levant (Syria, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine and Jordan), Sudan, Cyprus, Libya, Tunisia and Algeria.

The stuffing recipe is universal. Use it for your grape leaves and cabbage, and add more lemon! This is my style! Feel free to alter the spices to your liking & make it comfortable for your home. Add stuffed jalapeños for a spicy pot of #kusa 
. KUSA recipe 
4 cups soaked and cleaned cal rose rice
1 1/2 lb of coarse ground beef
One heaping spoon tomato paste
3 tablespoons of salt
1/2 cup of ghee
1 tablespoon of allspice
1 teaspoon of citric acid
1 teaspoon of pepper
optional
Pomegranate molasses

Broth
Beef or lamb bones boiled with tomato of your choice( i use both tomato paste and diced tomatoes or stewed tomatoes & as a cheat you can make use consome de rez) 
Salt and lemon with a little bit of pepper for flavor. 
Make sure you dig out and clean your Mexican squash. I prepare my Mexican squash the night before and I put them hole down so that the squash or not bitter.

Don’t overstuff your squash with rice mixture, and place them on top of the bones laying sideways and slightly pointing up so that the broth can enter the cavity of the squash. 
Make sure all squash is completely submerged in broth and cover with a heavy plate or even a pot. Bring pot to a boil then reduce heat and Cook for about an hour on medium low heat. 
Served with a side of cucumbers and yogurt.
